context: Within the diasporan Armenian community, there is an unofficial classification of the different kinds of Armenians. For example, <a0_0>Armenians who originate from Iran<a0_0/> are referred to as <b8_0>Parskahay<b8_0/> (Պարսկահայ), while <a1_0>Armenians from Lebanon<a1_0/> are usually referred to as <b9_0>Lipananahay<b9_0/> (Լիբանանահայ). Armenians of the Diaspora are the primary speakers of the <a2_0>Western<a2_0/> dialect of the Armenian language. This dialect has <a3_0>considerable differences with Eastern Armenian, but speakers of either of the two variations can <b5_0>usually understand each other<b5_0/><a3_0/>. <a4_0>Eastern<a4_0/> Armenian in the diaspora is primarily spoken in Iran and European countries such as Ukraine, Russia, and Georgia (where they form a majority in <b6_0>the Samtskhe-Javakheti province<b6_0/>).
